The issue is that RabbitMQ doesn't automatically propagate W3C `traceparent`/`tracestate` headers — you must inject them on publish and extract them on consume.

## Publisher (Service A)

```csharp
using System.Diagnostics;

// Create a shared ActivitySource for your app
static readonly ActivitySource Source = new("ServiceA.Messaging");

// When publishing:
using var activity = Source.StartActivity("OrderEvent publish", ActivityKind.Producer);

var props = channel.CreateBasicProperties();
props.Headers ??= new Dictionary<string, object>();

// Inject current trace context into message headers
DistributedContextPropagator.Current.Inject(
    activity, props.Headers, static (headers, key, value) =>
    {
        headers[key] = value;
    });

channel.BasicPublish(exchange, routingKey, props, body);
```

## Consumer (Service B)

```csharp
static readonly ActivitySource Source = new("ServiceB.Messaging");

// In your consumer callback:
DistributedContextPropagator.Current.ExtractTraceIdAndState(
    properties.Headers,
    static (headers, key) =>
    {
        var dict = (IDictionary<string, object>)headers;
        return dict.TryGetValue(key, out var val)
            ? val is byte[] bytes ? System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetString(bytes) : val?.ToString()
            : null;
    },
    out var traceParent,
    out var traceState);

// Rehydrate the parent context
ActivityContext parentCtx = default;
if (ActivityContext.TryParse(traceParent, traceState, out var parsed))
    parentCtx = parsed;

using var activity = Source.StartActivity(
    "OrderEvent consume",
    ActivityKind.Consumer,
    parentContext: parentCtx);  // ← links this span to Service A's trace

// ... handle the message
```

## Wire up OpenTelemetry (both services)

```csharp
builder.Services.AddOpenTelemetry()
    .WithTracing(t => t
        .AddSource("ServiceA.Messaging")   // or ServiceB.Messaging
        .AddAspNetCoreInstrumentation()
        .AddOtlpExporter());
```

## Why this works

| Step | What happens |
|---|---|
| **Inject** | `traceparent` + `tracestate` are written as RabbitMQ header bytes |
| **Extract** | Header bytes are decoded back to strings |
| **StartActivity(…, parentCtx)** | The consumer span becomes a **child** of the producer span |

The byte→string decode in the getter lambda is needed because RabbitMQ stores header values as `byte[]`.

**Tip:** If you switch to [MassTransit](https://masstransit.io/) or [NServiceBus](https://particular.net/nservicebus), this propagation is handled automatically.
